    <h1>How this site runs</h1>
    <p class="lede">This site is operated by Everlane&rsquo;s own studio automation. The listing data refreshes itself from the MLS; the market numbers are computed by a database, never guessed by a model; the pages regenerate on every deploy; and every client-facing word is the broker&rsquo;s. Here&rsquo;s exactly how &mdash; because a site that claims to be honest about data should be able to show its work.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" style="padding-top:10px">
  <div class="wrap">
    <h2>The pipeline</h2>
    <div class="prose prose--kb" style="margin-top:8px">
      <ol>
        <li><strong>The data comes straight from the MLS.</strong> Listings arrive through MLS GRID&rsquo;s licensed data feed &mdash; the same source the MLS itself publishes &mdash; refreshed every few hours. Nothing here is typed in by hand or scraped off another site.</li>
        <li><strong>A private mirror keeps it current.</strong> Each refresh updates our own copy of the listings; when the MLS changes or removes a listing, the mirror follows in the same cycle, so what you see tracks what&rsquo;s actually on the market.</li>
        <li><strong>Every market number is computed, not estimated.</strong> Medians, counts, and the other market figures are calculated by the database in plain arithmetic over real records &mdash; an AI model never writes a market number. If the data isn&rsquo;t there yet, the page shows nothing rather than a made-up figure.</li>
        <li><strong>The whole site rebuilds itself.</strong> When the data changes, every page is regenerated from scratch and redeployed &mdash; timestamped, so you can see how fresh each number is. There is no live database call between you and a stale page; the page you load was already rebuilt with the latest data.</li>
        <li><strong>A watchdog checks it hourly.</strong> A separate monitor confirms the feed is healthy every hour. If a refresh ever fails and the data goes stale, the site says so out loud &mdash; a visible banner &mdash; instead of quietly showing yesterday&rsquo;s numbers as if they were today&rsquo;s.</li>
      </ol>
      <p style="color:var(--c-sub)">The broker&rsquo;s entire monitoring duty is a short weekly digest of the pipeline&rsquo;s health. The machine does the watching; a person reads one email.</p>
    </div>

    <h2 style="margin-top:40px">Live counters</h2>
    <p class="lede" style="margin-top:6px">These fill in the moment the live MLS feed connects. Until then they stay empty on purpose &mdash; the same rule the whole site runs on: show you nothing before we&rsquo;ll show you a number we can&rsquo;t stand behind.</p>
    <div class="grid grid--2" style="margin-top:16px">
      <div class="card"><strong>Listings synced today</strong><p style="margin:6px 0 0"><span class="stub-note">Live when the feed connects</span></p></div>
      <div class="card"><strong>Pages refreshed on last deploy</strong><p style="margin:6px 0 0"><span class="stub-note">Live when the feed connects</span></p></div>
      <div class="card"><strong>AI drafts reviewed by the broker</strong><p style="margin:6px 0 0"><span class="stub-note">Live once draft-tracking is wired</span></p></div>
      <div class="card"><strong>Feed freshness</strong><p style="margin:6px 0 0"><span class="stub-note">Live when the feed connects</span></p></div>
    </div>

    <h2 style="margin-top:40px">What the automation never does</h2>
    <div class="prose prose--kb" style="margin-top:8px">
      <ul>
        <li><strong>It never publishes on its own.</strong> The studio&rsquo;s tools research and draft the guides and neighborhood chapters &mdash; but they never hit publish. Every change to what this site <em>says</em> is reviewed, edited, and merged by the broker before it goes live, one change at a time. No words reach you that a person didn&rsquo;t read, approve, and put his name to.</li>
        <li><strong>It never makes up a market number.</strong> Prices, medians, and counts are arithmetic done by the database over real MLS records. A model is never in that path. Missing data renders as an honest blank, not an estimate.</li>
        <li><strong>It never invents an answer.</strong> The AI concierge (in development) will answer only from this site&rsquo;s own published knowledge base and the live listings &mdash; it cannot reach beyond them, and it cannot guess. When it doesn&rsquo;t know, it says so and points you to the broker.</li>
        <li><strong>It never profiles who should live somewhere.</strong> Every neighborhood page describes the <em>place</em> &mdash; its features, its flood story, its housing stock &mdash; never the kind of person who &ldquo;belongs&rdquo; there. That&rsquo;s a fair-housing line the content is built to and checked against automatically.</li>
        <li><strong>It never stores private party data.</strong> Seller and occupant private fields from the MLS feed are stripped at the source, before anything is saved &mdash; they never reach this site or any tool behind it.</li>
        <li><strong>It will run under a cap and a log.</strong> When the AI concierge launches, it will operate under a hard spending limit with every query recorded &mdash; so it can be audited and can never quietly run away. (Site analytics already collect no personal information.)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="card" style="margin-top:28px">
      <p style="margin:0">This is a working brokerage site operated by a real broker &mdash; the automation exists to keep the data honest and current, not to replace the person you&rsquo;ll actually work with. <a href="/team/serge-osaulenko/">Meet the broker &rarr;</a></p>
    </div>
